	(text "\nThis board features a bifurcated architecture (MCU M1 = Motors, MCU M2 = Comms). \nBelow are the hard hardware limits and the supported customization paths.\n\n[1] HARD SYSTEM LIMITS (DO NOT EXCEED)\n----------------------------------------------------------------------\n* ABSOLUTE MAX INPUT VOLTAGE: ~26V DC. \n  The TVS Diode (D7) is an SMAJ24V. Sustained input voltages above 26V \n  will cause D7 to shunt to ground, blowing the main fuse or the diode.\n* LOGIC CURRENT LIMIT: 1.0 Amp. \n  The 5V regulator (VR2) and all logic/comms are protected by fuse F1. \n  Do not attempt to draw heavy auxiliary 5V power from the headers.\n* MOTOR CURRENT LIMIT: 3.0 Amps per channel (12A Total). \n  This is a hard silicon limit baked into the LM2576-ADJ regulators \n  (VR1, VR3, VR4, VR5). The flyback diodes (SS34) and inductors are \n  also strictly rated for 3A. You CANNOT increase this via firmware.\n\n[2] POWER SUPPLY CUSTOMIZATIONS\n----------------------------------------------------------------------\n* ADJUSTING MOTOR VOLTAGE (Currently ~8.85V): \n  The LM2576-ADJ regulators are set via resistor dividers. To change \n  a motor's voltage, swap its high-side (R_top) 62K resistor.\n  Formula: V_out = 1.23V * (1 + (R_top / 10K)).\n  - Motor 1 (VR1): Change R5\n  - Motor 2 (VR3): Change R19\n  - Motor 3 (VR4): Change R27\n  - Motor 4 (VR5): Change R39\n\n* CHANGING THE MAIN SYSTEM TO 12V:\n  The board is factory-locked to a 20V minimum input by the Under-\n  Voltage Lockout (UVLO) circuit. To run the board off a 12V supply, \n  you MUST physically replace Zener diode D11 (20V) with a 9V or 10V \n  Zener diode.\n\n[3] SENSOR NETWORKING (12V vs 24V RS485 SENSORS)\n----------------------------------------------------------------------\nThe 4-pin RS485 sensor ports (J5, J6, J8, J9) and the DWIN port (J1) \nroute the raw 'VIN' power net to Pin 4 to power external nodes. \nThere is NO dedicated 12V regulator on this board.\n* If you supply 24V to the main input (J4), the sensors receive 24V.\n* If you want to use strictly 12V RS485 sensors, you MUST:\n  1. Swap the D11 UVLO diode to 10V (as detailed above).\n  2. Power the entire board via a 12V main power supply. \n  (Note: Supplying 12V main power means your motor regulators can \n  now only output a maximum of ~10.5V due to voltage dropout).\n\n[4] MCU COMMUNICATION & ISOLATION\n----------------------------------------------------------------------\nM1 (Motors) and M2 (Comms) have NO physical copper data traces linking \nthem. They are designed to communicate wirelessly via dual LoRa modules \n(H3 & H4). \n* To establish a wired link, you must manually run jumper wires \n  between programming headers H1 and H2. \n* Turn SW1 OFF to disconnect M2's USB bridge and prevent data collisions \n  if routing UART over the H1/H2 pins.\n======================================================================"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 99.06 321.31 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
		)
